## Honest Limitations

This adapter is the lowest-common-denominator. It does **not** match Claude
Code's coverage. Read this section before relying on it.

- **No automatic telemetry.** {{TELEMETRY_GAP}}. Without telemetry, the weekly
  dead-skills report has no data to work with — it will report "no telemetry"
  until you instrument something.
- **No auto skill-router sync.** When you add or edit a `skills/<name>/SKILL.md`,
  you must run `node scripts/sync-local-skill-router.js` yourself (or wire a
  file-watcher — see the checklist).
- **No scheduled prune.** The weekly auto-prune is a script you can run manually
  or schedule via Windows Task Scheduler / cron / launchd / systemd timer.
  Grace period is **{{GRACE_PERIOD_DAYS}} days** of zero invocations before a
  skill becomes a prune candidate.
- **No SessionEnd hook.** Memory entries are written manually. The
  `agentic-prompt-architect` skill and the handoff procedure are the recommended
  end-of-session rituals.
- **Editor-specific features are out of scope.** Cursor's `.cursorrules`, Aider's
  `.aider.conf.yml`, Gemini CLI's `GEMINI.md` — if you want those, layer them on
  top of this file or use a dedicated adapter.

If you find yourself wishing the generic adapter did more, that's a signal to
build (or request) a dedicated adapter for your editor. The generic adapter
trades automation for portability. That's the point.
